# 🚀 Full Stack Deployment Guide
### React + Node/Express + MongoDB — Using Vercel, Render & MongoDB Atlas

This guide walks you through deploying a full stack MERN application for free using:
- **Vercel** → Frontend (React/Vite)
- **Render** → Backend (Node/Express)
- **MongoDB Atlas** → Database

---

## 📋 Prerequisites

- GitHub account with your project pushed
- Node.js installed locally
- Your project structure:
  ```
  project/
  ├── client/         # React/Vite frontend
  ├── server/         # Node/Express backend
  └── compose.yml
  ```

---

## STEP 1 — MongoDB Atlas (Database)

1. Go to [mongodb.com/atlas](https://mongodb.com/atlas) and **Sign Up** for free
2. Click **Create a Cluster** → choose **M0 Free Tier** → select any region → click **Create**
3. **Create a Database User:**
   - Left sidebar → **Database Access** → **Add New Database User**
   - Set a username and password (save these!)
   - Role → **Atlas Admin** → click **Add User**
4. **Whitelist All IPs:**
   - Left sidebar → **Network Access** → **Add IP Address**
   - Click **Allow Access from Anywhere** → enters `0.0.0.0/0`
   - Click **Confirm**
5. **Get Connection String:**
   - Click **Connect** on your cluster → **Drivers**
   - Copy the URI — looks like:
     ```
     mongodb+srv://username:password@cluster0.xxxxx.mongodb.net/yourdbname
     ```
   - Replace `<password>` with your actual password
   - Replace `yourdbname` with your database name (e.g. `mediconnect`)

✅ Atlas is ready!

---

## STEP 2 — Backend on Render

1. Go to [render.com](https://render.com) and **Sign Up with GitHub**
2. Click **New → Web Service**
3. Connect your GitHub repository → click **Connect**
4. **Configure the service:**

   | Setting | Value |
   |---|---|
   | Name | `your-app-server` |
   | Root Directory | `server` |
   | Language/Environment | `Docker` |
   | Branch | `main` or `master` |
   | Region | Choose closest to your users |
   | Instance Type | `Free` |

5. **Add Environment Variables** — scroll down and click **Add from .env**, then paste:
   ```
   PORT=5000
   MONGO_URI=mongodb+srv://username:password@cluster0.xxxxx.mongodb.net/yourdbname
   JWT_SECRET=any-long-random-secret-string
   JWT_EXPIRES_IN=7d
   CLIENT_URL=https://your-app.vercel.app
   ```
   > ⚠️ You'll update `CLIENT_URL` after Vercel deployment

6. Click **Deploy Web Service**
7. Wait 3–5 minutes for the build to complete
8. Once you see **"Your service is live 🎉"**, copy your Render URL:
   ```
   https://your-app-server.onrender.com
   ```

✅ Backend is live!

---

## STEP 3 — Frontend on Vercel

### Option A: Via Vercel Dashboard (Recommended)

1. Go to [vercel.com](https://vercel.com) and **Sign Up with GitHub**
2. Click **New Project** → **Import** your GitHub repository
3. **Configure the project:**

   | Setting | Value |
   |---|---|
   | Root Directory | `client` |
   | Framework Preset | `Vite` |
   | Build Command | `npm run build` |
   | Output Directory | `dist` |

4. **Add Environment Variables:**
   ```
   VITE_API_BASE_URL=https://your-app-server.onrender.com/api
   VITE_RAZORPAY_KEY_ID=your_key (if applicable)
   ```
5. Click **Deploy**
6. Copy your Vercel URL:
   ```
   https://your-app.vercel.app
   ```

### Option B: Via Vercel CLI

```bash
# Install CLI
npm install -g vercel

# Login
vercel login

# Deploy
cd client
vercel

# Deploy to production
vercel --prod
```

✅ Frontend is live!

---

## STEP 4 — Update CLIENT_URL on Render

Now that you have your Vercel URL, update Render:

1. Go to Render → your service → **Environment**
2. Find `CLIENT_URL` → **Edit**
3. Change to your actual Vercel URL:
   ```
   CLIENT_URL=https://your-app.vercel.app
   ```
   > ⚠️ No trailing slash `/` at the end!
4. Render will **auto-redeploy** with the new value

---

## STEP 5 — Update Vercel Environment Variables

1. Go to Vercel → your project → **Settings → Environment Variables**
2. Confirm `VITE_API_BASE_URL` is set to your Render URL:
   ```
   VITE_API_BASE_URL=https://your-app-server.onrender.com/api
   ```
3. If you changed anything → go to **Deployments** → click **Redeploy**

---

## STEP 6 — Fix CORS in server.js

Make sure your `server.js` allows your Vercel domain:

```js
const allowedOrigins = [
  process.env.CLIENT_URL,
  "http://localhost:5173",
  "https://your-app.vercel.app", // hardcode as backup
].filter(Boolean);

app.use(cors({
  origin: (origin, callback) => {
    if (!origin) return callback(null, true);
    if (allowedOrigins.includes(origin)) return callback(null, true);
    return callback(new Error("Not allowed by CORS"));
  },
  credentials: true,
}));
```

---

## STEP 7 — Fix vercel.json (React Router)

Make sure your `client/vercel.json` has this to prevent 404 on page refresh:

```json
{
  "rewrites": [
    {
      "source": "/(.*)",
      "destination": "/index.html"
    }
  ]
}
```

> ⚠️ Use `/index.html` not `/` — using `/` causes redirect loops!

